Before the third stage of the game, Lang Ping also said that the two teams are not good to deal with: " Osaka's game will be very difficult, we still have to be as serious as always, seriously prepare."
Now the defending horn has been sounded, the game has really entered the "white heat stage".
On the strength of the lineup, the Chinese women's volleyball team is above the opponent, but only the last critical moment, but also depends on whether the women's volleyball girls can play a normal level and release themselves on the field.
The University of Macau today (27) held the "Second Macao Stem Cell Symposium", attracting more than 100 experts and scholars from the United States, Singapore, the Mainland, Hong Kong and Macao and other countries and regions engaged in "outbound stem cell" research, and sharing and discussing the latest technology and development of stem cell research with teachers and students of Macao universities.
Ge Wei, Vice-Chancellor (Research) of the University of Australia, said that stem cell research has medical value and is one of the key scientific research projects of the University, which is a seminar to help promote Macao's research and development in the field of stem cells.
Ge Wei said that as a leading international comprehensive university on the west coast of the Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macao Greater Bay Area, the University is committed to building a talent training base and scientific and technological innovation center for the West Coast of the Greater Bay Area to help the innovation and development of the Bay Area.
The seminar brought together stem cell research experts at home and abroad to share the latest technology, which will help promote stem cell research and development in Macao.
Deng Xia, Dean of the College of Health Sciences, said that the University has continuously strengthened scientific research innovation and transformation in recent years, and has also significantly improved the number and quality of papers, and the University has also achieved fruitful results in stem cell research.
At the meeting, a group of well-known scholars shared the cutting-edge knowledge and cutting-edge technology of stem cell research.
Ji Weizhi, academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences and dean of the School of Spiritual Transformation of Yunnan Kunming University of Science and Technology, explained the use of 3D culture system to study the process and molecular mechanism of monkeys and human embryos in vitro; Jing Naihe, a researcher at the Shanghai Institute of Biochemical Cells of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, explained the spatial and temporal changes in the cell lineage decision and organization after implantation of mouse embryos from single cell and molecular level; Wang Yong, a professor at Pennsylvania State University, showed you how to use biomaterial hydrogel to simulate stem cell micro nests for survival and delivery.
Xu Renhe, Vice President (Research), Associate Professor of the University of Australia's College of Health Sciences, Chen Guokai, Assistant Dean, and Wang Chunming, Associate Professor of the Australian Institute of Chinese Medicine, also introduced their latest important results.
The "Second Macao Stem Cell Seminar" was organized by the School of Health Sciences of the University of Macau, co-organized by the Chinese Medical Research Institute of the University of Macau and the State Key Laboratory of Chinese Quality Research of the University of Science and Technology of Macao, and Chen Yongan, Acting Senior Manager of the Macao Science and Technology Development Fund.
The symposium included 11 academic reports on embryonic development and tissue generation, translational medicine, mechanism research and translational applications of stem cells, biomaterials and applications.
The atmosphere of the seminar was warm, and the participants actively discussed and shared the latest research and ideas on related technologies.
Xu Renhe said that the seminar provided a platform for exchanges and cooperation for stem cell experts in the Greater Bay Area and other regions, and also provided valuable learning opportunities for students.
