Make tea with plastic tea bags!
According to the Central News Agency, a new study in Canada recently found that a bag of plastic tea bags may release billions or even tens of billions of plastic particles, significantly higher than the amount of microplastics that a person is estimated to consume throughout the year, but so far there is no evidence that ingesting plastic particles poses a threat to humans.
According to reports, researchers at the University of Magill in Canada found that by dimmering a plastic tea bag into a cup of almost boiled hot water (95 degrees Celsius), the tea bag would release about 11.6 billion plastic particles and 3.1 billion smaller nanoplastic particles into the cup.
This amount is significantly higher than the amount of microplastics an estimated person consumes throughout the year.
According to research published earlier in 2019, the average person eats at least 50,000 microplastics a year and inhales the same amount of microplastics.
It is reported that the study was published in the Journal of Environmental Science and Technology, and the researchers tested four different types of plastic commercial tea bags in Montreal stores and cafes, opened the tea bags, immersed the tea bags in almost boiling water for 5 minutes after cleaning, and then analyzed them with electron microscopes and spectrometers.
According to the study, they found that a single tea bag released more than 11.6 billion plastic particles, "several times higher than the plastic load of other food before."
Most tea bags are made of natural fibers, but many brands that use natural fibers still use plastic to seal up.
Some branded tea bags have been made of paper and used plastic, and these plastic tea bags are the subject of the researchers.
Plastic particles are tiny fragments of plastics, and researchers have defined these microplastics to be between 100 nanometers and 5 mm, mainly due to the decomposition of plastic waste.
Researchers have found traces of plastic particles in the air, soil, rivers and deepest trenches around the world, and these microplastics can also be found in tap water, bottled water, seafood and beer.
In October 2018, researchers first found plastic particles in human stool samples in several countries in different regions of the world.
To test the potential toxicity of plastic particles released by tea bags, the Canadian research team put water flea into contaminated water and found that microplastics affected the behavior of these water fleas and caused them to develop deformities.
According to the World Health Organization (WHO), there is no evidence that ingesting plastic particles poses a threat to humans.
However, the WHO notes that more research is needed to fully understand how these plastics spread into the environment and what impact they have on humans.
The researchers speculate that the reason why these tea bags release a large amount of plastic particles may be that these plastic tea bags come into contact with boiling water, and even when the "edible grade" plastic is heated to more than 40 degrees Celsius, it may decompose or exud toxic substances.
