China Releases China and the United Nations, and Report on Climate Change and Sustainable Development
UNITED NATIONS, Sept. 26 (Xinhua) -- On September 26, the Chinese delegation to the 74th session of the United Nations General Assembly officially released four documents, including China and the United Nations - China's Position Paper on the 74th Session of the United Nations General Assembly, the United Nations Climate Action Summit: China's Position and Action, China's Progress Report on the Implementation of the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development (2019), and the Report on Earth's Big Data Supporting the Sustainable Development Goals.
The China Position Paper on China and the United Nations at the 74th session of the United Nations General Assembly summarizes the achievements and development of cooperation between China and the United Nations in various fields since the founding of New China 70 years ago, especially since the 18th CPC National Congress.
It is pointed out that the promotion of the construction of a community with a shared future for mankind proposed by Chinese President Xi Jinping has become the banner of great power diplomacy with Chinese characteristics.
Under the guidance of Xi Jinping's diplomatic thought, China has participated in international affairs with a more active and promising attitude, made greater contributions to world peace and development, and shouldered more responsibilities.
China has always been a builder of world peace, a contributor to global development and a defender of the international order.
The document introduces China's important contributions to the three pillars of peace, development and human rights of the United Nations from ten aspects.
Reaffirm that China firmly supports and practices multilateralism and supports the United Nations in playing a central role in international affairs; points out that China's development resonates with the same frequency and development of the world, and promotes each other; and emphasizes that in the face of the great changes that the world has not seen in a century, a developing China will contribute more and more positive energy to the world.
The United Nations Climate Action Summit: China's Position and Actions closely follow the nine major areas of action of the UN Climate Action Summit and introduce China's policy proposition on international cooperation on climate change and the achievements of China's measures to address climate change.
As the world's largest developing country, China regards climate change as an inherent requirement for its own sustainable development and its responsibility to build a community with a shared future for mankind, and will continue to overcome the many difficult challenges facing its own development, firmly safeguard multilateralism, implement international commitments, and make every effort to promote the full and effective implementation of the Paris Agreement.
China's Progress Report on the Implementation of the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development (2019) is the second progress report issued by China after the 2017 implementation progress report.
The report comprehensively sorted out China's measures, progress, challenges and next-step plans for implementing the 2030 Agenda, and demonstrated China's determination and achievements in implementing new development concepts and achieving high-quality development.
The report contains cases of precision poverty alleviation, innovation-led development, ecological civilization construction, rural revitalization, and joint construction of the “Belt and Road” that will provide useful reference for other countries to implement the 2030 Agenda.
The Earth Big Data Supports the Sustainable Development Goals Report shows China's use of Earth Big Data to support the exploration and practice of the implementation of the 2030 Agenda and policy decisions, reveals the application value and prospects of relevant technologies and methods for monitoring and evaluating the Sustainable Development Goals, and provides new perspectives and new support for the international community to fill data and methodology gaps and accelerate the implementation of the 2030 Agenda.
