The Fair Work Commission found that the owner of a Foodworks supermarket had slammed the "shame" for firing a 66-year-old female worker by text message because he preferred to hire employees from an Asian background.
The commission said the way Jianbin Wang, the owner of Ms. Gail Ayton, who has worked at the Wagga Wagga store for more than 20 years, treated employees in a "extremely unfair" way and may have violated anti-discrimination laws.
Ms Ayton told the committee that Mr. Wang had taken over the store in 2016 and that he had been “wanting to fire me” because she was not Chinese.
In this case, Peter Sams, vice chairman of the committee, conducted a search on the Internet and found that "Mr. Wang has posted some job advertisements on various Chinese-Australian employment forums in the past".
Of the job requirements listed for these positions, one said "first-choice Asian lady" and the other said "Asia employee preferred".
The third post said he was "more inclined to be overseas."
Mr Wang fired Ms Ayton via text message in April, later saying it was due to her absence and a small cash deficit from $5.10 to $30 at the cash register.
But Mr. Sams said Mr. Wang’s reasons for firing Ms Ayton were weak and there was a lack of evidence.
In the past three years, she has been absent from one shift, and the "missing amount" totals several Australian dollars.
He said Ms Ayton's firing "hasn't actually anything to do with her actions or actions".
"In my opinion, supported by the evidence of Mr. Wang's job advertisement, the real motive for the abhorrees' dismissal was that he would rather hire employees with Asian backgrounds," he said.
Under section 772(f) of the Fair Work Act, Mr. Wang's conduct ostensibly constitutes a violation of the Anti-Discrimination Act and/or an unlawful act of dismissal against the applicant.
Mr. Sams said it would be inappropriate for Wang to consider reinstating her position in view of the “horrible” treatment of Ms Ayton.
He should consider paying compensation to Ms Ayton, a temporary worker who earns $26 an hour.
In light of possible violations of anti-discrimination and industrial relations legislation, Sams said he would refer his ruling and documents to the committee’s director to consider whether Mr. Wang’s actions should be referred to other bodies to investigate possible violations of state or federal law.
He said Mr. Wang did not give Ms. Ayton any opportunity to respond to the alleged grounds for firing her.
"I believe that the apologist has taken an incorrigible unfair and biased process to dismiss the applicant, and Mr. Wang 'waits' for this opportunity, which he believes will 'justify' the termination of the applicant's employment," he said.
“He was wrong ... to dismiss the applicant in a total disregard for any natural and just treatment given to her, and it is shocking that he acted impertinently and grossly unjustly perfunctorily.”
Mr. Sams said that while Foodworks is a small business, “it must be frank that no decent employer will fire an employee in the manner admitted in this case to the extreme unfairness and perfunctory manner.”
He said, "It's shameful and it's grossly unfair."
