World's oldest barber dies at 108, haircuts 96 years
Anthony Mancinelli, the world's oldest barber certified by the world's Guinness Book of World Records, is a 108-year-old who never retired to pay a daily barber for a guest, but on the 19th Mancinelli died of complications from jaw cancer, saying goodbye to his 96-year-long haircut.
According to CNN, Mansinelli immigrated to the United States when he was 8 years old, and soon helped clean the floor at a barbershop, and at the age of 12, he began to pick up scissors to serve guests, thereby reducing the economic pressure on the family.
Mancinelli attended elementary school at the time, but did not graduate.
Mancinelli's son, Robert, revealed that his father loved work and people from all over the world loved him, but although his father was always healthy, he was diagnosed with cancer in February this year, and finally could not work due to physical factors six weeks before his death, but this was not retirement, because he planned to come back to cut his hair when he was better.
Robert, 82, said he now had to find a new barber after his father died because he had asked him to help him cut his hair all his life.
Listed companies repurchase scale of more than 100 billion yuan reached a record high - Xinhua
In order to stabilize the company's stock price and maintain the company's image, listed companies have begun to frequently repurchase shares in the past two years, and hope to pass the information on the company's undervalued value to the market through targeted repurchases and collective bidding transactions, so as to stabilize the stock price and enhance investor confidence.
Oriental Fortune Choice data show that in 2017, listed companies to repurchase shares of the funds for 7.9 billion yuan, soared to 51 billion yuan in 2018, since 2019, the total amount of A-share listed companies repurchase implementation has exceeded 100 billion yuan, setting a new high in the amount of A-shares have been repurchased, and far exceeded the previous year.
From the perspective of the purpose of repurchase, the company's repurchase of shares and the increase of major shareholders seem to be the same, but there are great differences in terms of implementation, source of funds, repurchase use, and equity of the shares themselves.
Xu Yang, chairman of Shanghai Mei Kerong Information Consulting Co., Ltd., said in an interview with the "Securities Daily" reporter that in November 2018, the "Opinions on Supporting the Repurchase of Shares by Listed Companies" was revised for the problems of the current system such as the narrow scope of share repurchase, complicated decision-making procedures and inadequate inventory system.
In January this year, the SSE and the Shenzhen Stock Exchange officially released the "implementation rules for repurchasing shares of listed companies", the introduction of these policies, broadened the listed companies to buy back the source of funds, appropriate simplification of the implementation procedures, guidance and improvement of governance arrangements, to encourage all kinds of listed companies to implement equity incentives or employee stock ownership plans.
After the introduction of the opinion, the operation of the stock repurchase of listed companies has more applicable circumstances, the repurchase process is simpler, and the enthusiasm for share repurchase is greater.
Repurchasing shares in a relatively low position is also conducive to listed companies to improve the efficiency of the use of funds, thereby increasing the level of earnings per share, increasing the return on net assets, and reducing the pressure on the company's profit indicators.
Compared with the increase of major shareholders, the repurchase of shares by listed companies is of greater significance, and it also reflects the willingness of listed companies to actively manage market value and abundant cash flow.
Xu Yang believes that the stock price is undervalued as the main factor for the repurchase of listed companies, and the company's share price has not reflected the company's future development prospects, so such companies deserve the attention of investors, but they cannot blindly invest, and they need to pay attention to the financial reports of such listed companies and the specific business situation.
Listed companies with large-scale repurchases have at least shown the company's development confidence and financial strength.
The enthusiasm for repurchases of A-share listed companies has gradually heated up, which has also normalized the repurchase behavior, and the data shows that nearly a thousand listed companies have implemented share repurchases this year, and leading companies in various industries have become the main force in the repurchase market.
China Ping An recently disclosed repurchase progress that the company has repurchased 57.59 million shares of A shares through centralized bidding transactions, accounting for 0.315% of the company's total share capital, and the total amount of funds paid has been 5 billion yuan (excluding transaction fees), and the repurchased shares will be used for employee stock ownership plans, including but not limited to the long-term service plan that has been considered at the company's shareholders meeting.
Yili shares have paid 5.792 billion yuan for share repurchase, and in the recent adjustment of the use of repurchased shares, from the original plan "repurchase shares will be used as a source of stock for the later implementation of equity incentives" to "accumumulated repurchase of 183 million shares, of which 152 million shares for the implementation of equity incentive stock source, the remaining 30.49 million shares will be used to cancel to reduce the registered capital."
Yili said that the cancellation of some of the repurchased shares is conducive to further improving the level of earnings per share and effectively improving the return on investment of the company's shareholders.
TCL Group issued a repurchase progress announcement on September 25, showing that TCL Group repurchased 3.59% of the company's shares, costing a total of 1.65 billion yuan.
The office of the board of directors of TCL Group told the Securities Daily reporter that the repurchased shares will be used for employee stock ownership plans, equity incentives or corporate bonds that can be converted into stocks issued by listed companies.
TCL Group adheres to the established business strategy, continuously improves competitiveness and continues to develop healthily.
Based on the confidence in the company's future development and the protection of investors' interests, combined with the performance of the company's stock in the secondary market for nearly a year, and taking into account the company's operating situation and financial situation and other factors, the company plans to use its own funds, self-financing and other financing methods to buy back the company's shares.
Yang Delong, chief economist of Qianhai Open Source Fund, said that the operation of listed companies to buy back shares, on the one hand, can reduce the number of shares circulating in the market, increase the earnings per share of listed companies, which is an important benefit for the share price of the secondary market; in addition, listed companies are willing to take the initiative to take out real gold and silver, and buy back shares from the stock market.
The repurchase of domestic listed companies has gradually increased in recent years, especially the performance of high-performing stocks, and it is a very good way to boost investor confidence through share repurchases, and it is also a practice worthy of recognition and encouragement.
