French finance minister says he will cut taxes by more than 10 billion euros next year and calls on Germany to follow suit
PARIS, Sept 26 (Reuters) - France will cut taxes by more than 10 billion euros ($10.9 billion) next year, French Finance Minister Bruno Le Maire said on Thursday, and that Germany should keep pace with France's fiscal stimulus to revive its sluggish economy.
Introducing France’s 2020 budget, Le Maire said the ECB’s latest monetary easing initiative has created an opportunity for member governments that can afford them to invest.
The European Central Bank cut interest rates to a record low on September 12 and plans to restart bond purchases in hopes of incentivizing economic recovery and pushing up inflation.
“Low interest rates will not allow Europe to prosper again, and monetary policy measures are necessary but not enough,” Le Maire told reporters.
"Germany needs to invest, it needs to be, the sooner the better. Don't wait until the situation gets worse before it acts," he added.
He has made this call to Germany on several occasions.
France has already implemented more than 10 billion euros in tax cuts this year, which has given a big boost to France's economic growth.
The global economy has lost momentum, and the German economy, which relies on exports, has borne the brunt.
Le Maire pointed out that the tax burden of French families will be reduced by 9.3 billion euros next year, including 5 billion euros in income tax relief.
In addition, with the gradual reduction of the corporate tax rate from 33.3% to 25% over the five-year period, the corporate tax burden will be reduced by nearly 1 billion euros.
