Study: U.S. National Healthy Eating Index Increases Slightly, but Still Challenging
Recently, a new study in the United States shows that in the past 16 years, the US government's healthy diet index has increased moderately, from 56 to 58.
But with a score of 100, it’s not worth celebrating.
U.S. citizens still face “significant challenges” in their diet.
One of the study’s authors, Dr. Fang Fang Zhang, a nutrition researcher at Tufts University in Massachusetts, said Americans still consume too much food that can cause heart disease, diabetes, obesity and other diseases, which are the most common diseases in the United States.
The study was published in the Journal of the American Medical Association on the 24th.
The study is based on the findings of a U.S. government health survey of 44,000 adults conducted between 1999 and 2016.
The authors write that "significant dietary challenges remain despite considerable improvements."
These challenges include allowing U.S. citizens to reduce their intake of snacks, hot dogs, fat cows, butter and other foods containing saturated fat.
The study found that people's daily dietary intake of these unhealthy fats increased from 11.5% to 12%, exceeding the recommended upper limit of 10%.
The biggest improvement in the U.S. diet is that sugar intake has been reduced from 16% to about 14%, but the intake is still too high.
The official opinion that the intake of added sugar should be less than 10% in the daily diet.
For the reasons for the reduction in sugar intake, the researchers believe that it is related to the reduction of people drinking sweet soda, but Zhang Fangfang stressed that sugar is often added to even less sweet foods, such as yogurt and ketchup.
U.S. adults have a small increase in their intake of fruits, nuts, oats, and other whole grain categories.
However, data from 2016 shows that these foods still account for less than 5% of the daily diet.
Although people's intake of salt has decreased slightly, and the reduction in drinking fruit juice has led to low-quality carbohydrate intake, Zhang Fangfang said that they still account for up to 42% of daily calories, many of which come from refined white bread and other refined grains.
The study was based on a biennial personal health survey that allowed adults to recall the food they had eaten in the past 24 hours.
These health surveys have asked this question twice every few days since 2003.
The government's dietary guidelines for U.S. residents recommend adopting a "healthy eating pattern" to reduce the likelihood of chronic disease.
The guidelines state that people should consume more nutrient-dense foods, such as vegetables, fruits, whole grains, low-fat dairy products, and seafood, lean meats, poultry meats, eggs, and seed foods that can provide protein.
The number of people with diabetes in the U.S. nearly doubled, more than 7 percent, during the study period, and obesity rates increased over many years of the studyâ€”more than 70 percent of U.S. adults are now overweight or obese.
Heart disease remains the leading cause of death in the United States.
