On the morning of the 26th, after the final vote in the New South State House of Representatives, the New South African abortion was legalized.
The bill allows a woman to terminate her pregnancy at 22 weeks of pregnancy and, if two doctors agree, also allow a woman to have an abortion later in the pregnancy.
The Senate passed an amendment on the evening of the 25th, that doctors can seek advice from the multidisciplinary panel of the hospital's advisory committee before performing an abortion procedure for a woman after 22 weeks of pregnancy.
In addition, the Senate-passed amendment also includes that doctors must provide appropriate care for babies who survive after terminating their pregnancy.
New South Carolina Gov. Berejiklian has faced public criticism from conservatives on the bill, and Berejikilian has intervened several times to gain more debate time for the bill, but she did not attend the final vote.
"I need to spend time running the entire NSW state," Berijiklen defended her absence vote.
Davis, a Liberal MP who was the strongest opponent of the abortion bill, threatened to withdraw from the NSW government because of the bill, and said the bill triggered a "government crisis".
But then Davis made a concession.
"The content of the amendment to the abortion legalization bill submitted to the House of Representatives on the morning of the 26th actually provides more protection for women and doctors," Davis said.
Meanwhile, Australian NSW National Party leader Bariraro said he was proud to be part of a government that legalized abortion.
"What we achieved last night is historic in New York, which legalizes abortion, is no longer a crime, and women who have abortions are not treated as criminals."
