U.S. Senate approves Scalia as Labor Secretary
WASHINGTON, Sept. 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate voted on the 26th to approve President Trump's nomination of Eugene Scalia as Secretary of Labor.
The vote was 53 in favor and 44 against, with no Democrats voting in favor of Scalia.
Republicans believe Scalia’s résumé makes him a perfect fit for the secretary of labor.
But in the eyes of Democrats, Scalia has long been the antithesis of workers and unions in his career as a lawyer.
Scalia will replace Alexander Acosta.
Acosta, then-Secretary of Labor, announced his resignation in July after being accused of "lenison" over alleged sexual assault and trafficking of teenage girls, American billionaire Jeffrey Epstein, who was accused of sexually assaulting and trafficking.
Scalia, 56, is a partner at a prominent U.S. law firm whose father is the late U.S. Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia.
The Department of Labor is the cabinet-level department of the federal government, which is responsible for labor-related matters.
The White House also issued a statement on the same day that Trump has nominated Peter Genet, the acting administrator of the Federal Emergency Management Agency, to officially lead the agency.
According to the procedure, Gayner's nomination must also be approved by the Senate.
The Federal Emergency Management Agency (D) is part of the Department of Homeland Security and coordinates the federal government’s resources to address emergencies such as natural disasters, terrorist attacks and other emergencies in the United States.
