Iran confirmed to develop advanced centrifuges to further suspend compliance with Iran nuclear deal
According to the Central News Agency, the United Nations International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) said on the 26th that Iran has once again violated the Iranian nuclear agreement by using advanced centrifuges to manufacture enriched uranium.
According to reports, Iran is gradually violating the restrictions of the Iranian nuclear agreement in response to US President Trump's withdrawal from the Iran nuclear agreement in May 2018, and restoring and strengthening sanctions against Iran.
Iran suspended two other commitments in July to keep the stockpile of enriched uranium below 300 kilograms and the purity of enriched uranium to no more than 3.67 percent.
Under the nuclear deal, Iran could only set up about 5,000 first-generation IR-1 centrifuges in Natanz to enrich uranium, and only allowed Iran to use a small number of more advanced models for research, but not to produce enriched uranium.
If Iran succeeds in developing more advanced centrifuges, it will be able to produce enriched uranium several times faster, possibly for the use of nuclear bombs.
According to the report, the IAEA report said: "On September 25, the agency confirmed that Iran's advanced centrifuges of model 2 and 3 ... are accumulating or are ready to accumulate enriched uranium."
The U.N. International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) presented the report to Member States on the 26th, and a diplomat responded by saying, “They are busy at the (Natanza enrichment) facility.”
