Italy’s education minister has proposed a sugar tax to protect people’s health.
Lorenzo Fioramonti, Italy’s new government’s minister of education and a member of the Five Star Movement, has introduced a motion to parliament recommending that the Italian government implement a new tax policy on sugar-highly high-sugar drinks, snacks and airline tickets.
According to reports, according to the bill proposed by Education Minister Fioramonti, the Italian government will impose a snack tax on food products such as sugary drinks and snacks that endanger health; at the same time, the environmental tax on airline tickets is imposed, domestic flights are levied 1 euro, and international classes are levied 1.5 euros.
Fioramonti said that through this seemingly small series of tax measures, the Italian government is expected to receive 3 billion euros in tax revenue.
The proceeds will be available in the areas of education, health and environmental protection.
In response, Italian Prime Minister Conte said that he believes this is a feasible solution; Italian MP, European Parliamentarian, League leader Salvini tweeted sarcastically that everyone should quickly hide desserts, biscuits, bread and candy, because the new government will start to impose a snack tax.
