Is it hard to move?
According to the Russian satellite network, a study of athletes shows that after high-intensity exercise, the brain will also show signs of fatigue.
The study, led by Mathias Pésigrigler, an expert at the Pitier-Salpetriel Hospital in France, shows that there is an unobtvious link between mental and physical labor: both require cognitive control of activity.
"You need to control the process of autonomy that can force yourself to stop when you have muscle and joint pain," explains Pésigler.
The study was initiated by the French National Institute of Sport and Physical Education (INSEP).
The school’s experts guide athletes in preparing for the Olympics.
Some athletes have begun to suffer from overtraining syndrome, that is, they have an irrepressible feeling of fatigue after high-load exercise, their physical inability to recover, and their performance has declined.
INSEP raises the question: Could part of this condition be neurological fatigue, the type of neurological fatigue caused by excessive mental labor?
The study was published in the journal Current Biology.
